# Crowd Counting Datasets: Comparative Analysis & Test Suite

This document compares five public crowd-counting datasets suitable for evaluating the YOLOv8 person detector in urban traffic and crowd safety applications.

---

## 1. Dataset Comparison Matrix

| Dataset | Images | Avg. Count / Image | Density Range | Primary Difficulty | Download Links / Repositories | Hackathon Demo Suitability |
| :--- | :---: | :---: | :---: | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **ShanghaiTech Part A** | 482 | 501.4 | 33 to 3,139 | Extremely high density, random internet camera perspectives, random scales. | [Kaggle Dataset Link](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/tannergi/shanghaitech-with-people-density-maps) | **Stress Test**: Useful for demonstrating the baseline failure of bounding-box detectors. |
| **ShanghaiTech Part B** | 716 | 123.6 | 9 to 576 | Surveillance camera perspective, variable outdoor shadows, street level depth. | [Kaggle Dataset Link](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/tannergi/shanghaitech-with-people-density-maps) | **🥇 BEST FOR TRAFFIC DEMO**: Matches CCTV street perspectives of Bengaluru Traffic Police. |
| **UCF_CC_50** | 50 | 1,279.5 | 94 to 4,633 | Very small dataset, extreme packing, massive scale variation, perspective compression. | [Kaggle Dataset Link](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/anirbanstark/ucf-cc-50) | **Defensive Design Case**: Proves the complete model collapse of standard object detectors. |
| **NWPU Crowd** | 5,109 | 361.3 | 0 to 20,033 | Large scale, negative samples (empty streets), extreme weather, variable lighting. | [Official Bench Link](http://www.crowdbenchmark.com/nwpucrowd.html) | **Scientific Validation**: Best for training and formal benchmarking, too large for quick live demos. |
| **JHU-CROWD++** | 4,372 | 1,114.2 | 0 to 25,111 | Annotations for weather (rain, snow), illumination (night), and occlusion levels. | [Official Bench Link](http://www.crowdbenchmark.com/jhucrowd.html) | **Robustness Auditing**: Ideal for testing the detector under adverse environmental conditions. |

---

## 2. In-Depth Comparative Evaluation

### A. ShanghaiTech Part A vs. Part B (The Baseline Standard)
* **Part A** comprises images scraped from the internet. The crowds are extremely dense and packed shoulder-to-shoulder (e.g. massive concerts, political protests). YOLOv8 detects almost nothing (<5%) in Part A because of massive occlusion.
* **Part B** comprises images captured from street surveillance cameras in Shanghai. The perspective is stationary and matches CCTV setups. The density is medium-sparse. YOLOv8 can successfully detect pedestrians in the foreground, making Part B a highly realistic dataset for testing street crossing flows.

### B. UCF_CC_50 (The Stress Benchmark)
* UCF_CC_50 is a legacy dataset containing only 50 images, but they are extremely dense (stadiums, religious gatherings, massive concerts).
* **YOLOv8 Evaluation:** It acts as a benchmark to demonstrate detector *collapse*. If YOLOv8 is evaluated on UCF_CC_50, the MAE is high (often missing >1000 people per frame). This is the scientific justification for needing density map estimation.

### C. NWPU Crowd vs. JHU-CROWD++ (The Large-Scale Standard)
* **NWPU** is currently the largest and most diverse crowd counting dataset. It has strict quality control and includes images with zero people, which is crucial to test if the model generates false positives on busy city pavements.
* **JHU-CROWD++** includes rich attributes (e.g., labels for rainy, snowy, or low-light scenes). This allows you to evaluate whether YOLOv8's accuracy degrades under heavy Bengaluru rain or night lighting.

---

## 3. Which Subset is Best for a Hackathon Demo?

### **🥇 Recommendation: ShanghaiTech Part B**
For a **Bengaluru Traffic Police AI Command Center** project, **ShanghaiTech Part B** is the most effective dataset for a live demonstration:
1. **Surveillance Alignment:** The images are taken from fixed street CCTV surveillance cameras. This aligns exactly with the input source of your project.
2. **Actionable Densities:** Pedestrian counts range from 9 to 576. These are actionable numbers where a traffic control center can choose to adjust signal splits or deploy local barricades.
3. **Detector Success Visibility:** YOLOv8 can detect a reasonable portion of the pedestrians in the foreground. This makes the bounding box overlay visualization look active and successful, which is highly satisfying for judges compared to a completely blank screen.

